metadata.name: Takashi's Death #100
metadata.description:
Akira by Katsuhiro Otomo.
A global landmark in the shaping of the Cyberpunk genre, and a watershed title for the medium.

I got my hands on the tank≈çbon(s) more than 20 years ago and those pages upon pages at the end of the third one depicting the destruction of Neo-Tokyo stayed with me ever since. Pages of stunning destruction, leaving me in awe.

This is my generative take on the subject. An attempt to evoke the power of that one panel in a cohesive collection.

Everything procedurally generated at runtime.
You can find more info on the composition here : https://ulucode.com/wp/takashis-death/

Export a PNG capture at various resolutions by pressing the number keys 1 to 9 (top row or numpad, and only in live mode, after pressing "open"). Resolutions ranges from 720 to 7680 pixels ( height ). I recommend starting with "4".

More features are available, but a decent GPU is recommended:
- Press "space" to toggle an animation on/off
- Press "u" to Unlock the camera. You can then :
. Mouse left : Rotate
. Mouse middle/wheel : Zoom
. Mouse right : Translate
. "r" : reset camera
. "a" : change antialiasing quality : 3 settings in rotation. Try this if your framerate is too low.

metadata.name: Refactor #15
metadata.description:
Future royalties are shared 50% with the original minters!

What is Refactor?

Refactor is a generative art series based on making noise with shapes while continuously rewriting the code to make it more clear and efficient. My ultimate goal was to add more variety to my generative art collections, improve my use of color, and create a work of art that the community will enjoy.

What was learned?

Rewriting code is similar to wiping off a failed oil painting. Sometimes it‚Äôs better to start over rather than waste time struggling to save what is destined to fail. The code for this token was re-written 3 times and can still be improved. Overall, I‚Äôm very pleased with the outputs and even more pleased with the knowledge and skills I developed throughout the creative process.

I learned how to create reusable custom functions for generating noise and adding borders. I also learned to construct custom shapes and overlays. Lastly, I now understand how to add rarity traits making this my first token to feature them. Good luck on minting a rare edition!

Why is there a Red Dot in the bottom corner?

The red dot is my signature for this series. It‚Äôs a shoutout to my first fxHash project titled ‚ÄúRed Dot‚Äù. I will continue to utilize red dots as a signature design element in future work.

About the token

- The overall canvas size is responsive based on your viewport
- Press ‚Äús‚Äù to save (image file type is SVG)
- Owners will be given priority access to future reserve lists
- Coded using p5js & SVGCanvas v2.0.3


About the Artist

Robert Matheson is a community engaged artist from Newberry, South Carolina. His work is focused on improving the health and well-being of others through the arts. In 2019 Robert established Newberry Made, a local artist & maker registry that has grown to over 180 members.

Robert's most recent creation is the NFT Museum of Newberry, SC. A creative space focused on providing NFT art education, collaboration and exhibition to help artists and the broader community benefit from emerging digital economies. Learn more at www.RobertMatheson.com and www.NonFungibleTokenMuseum.org

metadata.name: Bound #6
metadata.description:
Knots bind and hold, mark time, and unite. But the power of a well-tied knot isn't only to fasten ‚Äì it also symbolizes how tightly one holds their pledges. Whether a commitment to a partner, community, or oneself ‚Äì the longevity of a deeply held bond is often marked with a symbol of passing time, like knots tied in a rope.

Let these ropes remind us of the binds we hold ‚Äì new ones, lengthy ones, unbreakable ones, and even those we‚Äôve had to untie. In plain view, these knots invite us to contemplate what our bonds mean to us, and to see them anew.

---

metadata.name: The Age of Automata #84
metadata.description:
This is an exploration of cellular automaton to find simplicity and beauty in mathematics.

First, a grid with random dimensions is created. A color palette is randomly selected from a large number of palettes, and a cellular automaton is formed based on one of the rules, and this operation may be repeated randomly to form a relatively more complex pattern. Finally, a number of geometries are combined with the automaton to make the mint harmonious and unique.

The idea was inspired by discoveries of Wolfram and Ciphrd‚Äôs artwork. 

Press ‚Äôs‚Äô on the live mode to save the artwork.

I recently launched my Twitter, so if you have any questions and would like to know about my next work or have a suggestion, you can contact me through this account:

https://twitter.com/_XSaha

Made with P5js.

metadata.name: Ghrian #339
metadata.description:
Dutch auction (13/11/9/6/3), with price decreasing every 10 minutes after the start of the auction until 9 tez. Price will then decrease to 6 tez after 2 hours, then to 3 after 12 hours.

A selection of 33 different palettes.

The brush draw is determined by angles, shapes, randomly chosen overdraws, brush sizes and widths, among other things.

- Left arrow = draw in 2125x1375
- Right arrow = draw in 11x17 landscape mode fit to screen height
- Up arrow = draw in 1375x2125
- Down arrow = draw in 11x17 portrait mode fit to screen width
- Enter = draw in full window
- Tab = draw in 1400x1400
- Shift = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides
- Alt = draw in 1:1 aspect ratio scaled to window height with 5% border on all sides (default pixel density)
- Left mouse click = save as a png

Pixel density is set to 2 for all of the options above unless noted otherwise.

Please note that the drawing can take quite a while to run, especially in the full screen modes.

See thread below for additional details:

https://twitter.com/AndwerEric/status/1492619586931413000?s=20&t=N8joIBuTNzYYjmcBex0QJQ

metadata.name: Morphing Convictions #4
metadata.description:
Everyday we move on by relying on our convictions. Their immutability often helps us take decisions or take shelter but can sometimes clash with the unknown, the different and the new. They can then crack, crumble and mutate. To change your convictions means changing the kind of person you want to be. It means changing your self-identity. And that is not just hard, it is scary. And beautiful.

Morphing Convictions is a piece that exists through two kind of outputs : Posters and Scenes. Posters are focusing on the contemplation of details and movements of a morphing conviction while the Scenes are interactive little worlds where you can explore a conviction in it's environment.

Please open in live mode to enjoy a much better experience.

Controls :

Posters & Scenes
‚Ä¢ Click anywhere to enable audio.
‚Ä¢ Press M to toggle mute.
‚Ä¢ Press F to toggle the fullscreen mode.
‚Ä¢ Press 1, 2, 3, or 4 to make a capture and download a PNG with a resolution of x1, x2, x3 or x4.

Scenes only
‚Ä¢ Drag and scroll to rotate and zoom.
‚Ä¢ Click on objects, some might react.

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

Morphing Convictions by Ferdinand Dervieux, 2022
Made with Unity
